>
    <p>Your water heater is one of the most important appliances in your home, yet it often gets overlooked until problems arise. Regular maintenance can extend its lifespan, improve efficiency, and prevent costly emergency repairs.</p>

    <h2>Understanding Your Water Heater</h2>
    
    <p>Most South African homes use one of two types:</p>
    
    <h3>Storage Tank Water Heaters</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Store and continuously heat water</li>
        <li>More common in residential homes</li>
        <li>Typical lifespan: 8-12 years</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Tankless Water Heaters</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Heat water on demand</li>
        <li>More energy-efficient</li>
        <li>Longer lifespan: 15-20+ years</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Essential Maintenance Tasks</h2>

    <h3>1. Flush Your Tank Regularly</h3>
    <p><strong>Recommended frequency:</strong> Annually</p>
    <p>Sediment accumulates at the bottom of storage tanks, reducing efficiency and lifespan. Flushing removes this buildup.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Turn off the water heater</li>
        <li>Connect a hose to the drain valve</li>
        <li>Drain water into a bucket or floor drain</li>
        <li>Refill the tank</li>
        <li>Resume normal operation</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Note:</strong> This should be done by a professional if you're uncomfortable doing it yourself.</p>

    <h3>2. Check the Pressure Relief Valve</h3>
    <p>The T&P (Temperature & Pressure) valve is a critical safety feature.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Test it annually by lifting the lever</li>
        <li>A small amount of water should discharge</li>
        <li>If nothing happens or water flows continuously, replacement is needed</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3. Inspect the Anode Rod</h3>
    <p>This sacrificial rod prevents tank corrosion.</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Should be inspected every 3 years</li>
        <li>Replace when significantly corroded</li>
        <li>Proper maintenance extends tank life significantly</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>4. Maintain Appropriate Temperature</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Set thermostat to 120-125°C (for safety and efficiency)</li>
        <li>Higher temperatures waste energy and increase corrosion</li>
        <li>Check annually that temperature is correct</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>5. Inspect for Leaks</h3>
    <p>Check regularly for:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Water pooling around the base</li>
        <li>Rust stains</li>
        <li>Water dripping from connections</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Even small leaks can indicate bigger problems. Have them inspected professionally.</p>

    <h3>6. Insulate the Tank and Pipes</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Better insulation reduces heat loss</li>
        <li>Improves efficiency</li>
        <li>Reduces operating costs</li>
        <li>Wrap tank with insulation blankets</li>
        <li>Insulate hot water pipes</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Warning Signs of Water Heater Problems</h2>
    
    <ul>
        <li>No hot water or only lukewarm water</li>
        <li>Rusty or discolored water</li>
        <li>Strange noises (rumbling, popping)</li>
        <li>Water leaking from the tank</li>
        <li>Foul odors from hot water</li>
        <li>Higher than normal utility bills</li>
        <li>Age over 10 years (for storage heaters)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Extend Your Water Heater's Life</h2>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Regular maintenance:</strong> Annual professional inspections</li>
        <li><strong>Flush annually:</strong> Remove sediment buildup</li>
        <li><strong>Install a water softener:</strong> If you have hard water</li>
        <li><strong>Maintain appropriate temperature:</strong> Avoid excessively high settings</li>
        <li><strong>Address leaks immediately:</strong> Don't wait for professional repairs</li>
        <li><strong>Consider upgrades:</strong> When approaching end of life</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>When to Replace vs. Repair</h2>

    <h3>Repair if:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Water heater is less than 8 years old</li>
        <li>Problem is with specific component (thermostat, valve)</li>
        <li>Repair cost is less than 30-50% of replacement</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Replace if:</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Water heater is over 10 years old</li>
        <li>Tank is leaking</li>
        <li>Frequent repairs are needed</li>
        <li>Running costs have increased significantly</li>
        <li>Not producing enough hot water</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Professional Maintenance Benefits</h2>

